</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="200" pageNumber="478" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6707526" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6707526" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6707526/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="200" pageNumber="478" targetBox="[1454,2046,1445,1860]" targetPageId="200">
<paragraph blockId="200.[2068,2661,1441,1864]" pageId="200" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2069,2245,1674,1707]" pageId="200" pageNumber="478">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the type locality in SE Brazil.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="200" pageNumber="478" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="200.[2068,2661,1441,1864]" pageId="200" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2069,2312,1756,1785]" pageId="200" pageNumber="478">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 66-101 mm, tail 48-76 mm, ear 11-18 mm, hindfoot (without claw) 17-20 mm. No specific
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="200.[1455,2661,1871,2455]" pageId="200" pageNumber="478">
data are available for body weight. The Caparao Grass Mouse is a small-sized species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1496,1594,1910,1943]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Akodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="200" pageNumber="478" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Akodon</taxonomicName>
. Dorsum is grayish brown; sides are slightly paler than dorsum, with phaeomelanic bands generally very pale yellow; venter is grayish, with dark gray basal bands and terminal whitish bands; dark rostral patch occurs on some specimens, apparently more frequent on males than females. Tail is well-furred and bicolored, black dorsally and white ventrally; forefeet and hindfeet are covered by overall light gray tone.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="200" pageNumber="478" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="200.[1455,2661,1871,2455]" pageId="200" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1456,1567,2107,2140]" pageId="200" pageNumber="478">Habitat.</emphasis>
Cool, humid, and high-elevation grasslands and gallery montane habitats at elevations above 1800 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
